video_title: THE World Academic Summit 2018: National University of Singapore (NUS)
video_description:
Times Higher Education‚Äôs World Academic Summit 2018 will be held in partnership with the National University of Singapore (NUS) from 25 September - 27 September. 

The event, which brings together senior university, government and industry leaders in one of the most prestigious gatherings of its kind in the world, will focus on the theme: ‚ÄúThe transformative power of research: advancing knowledge, driving economies, building nations‚Äù.

The summit will follow on from the success of last year‚Äôs flagship event, which took place at King‚Äôs College London this week and was attended by more than 450 senior leaders from 52 countries.

video_title: Introducing the THE World Summit Series Network
video_description:
Join the THE World Summit Series Network today and enjoy access to our full programme of virtual and in-person events for an annual cost-saving fee.

Not only will you stay informed about the latest developments in global higher education, but you will also have the opportunity to network with colleagues, both in-person and online, and gain access to bespoke content and THE's unique datasets.

The network provides full access to world-class speakers and THE‚Äôs own in-house experts to help you learn about the biggest transformational changes in global higher education live and on-demand at your own convenience.

Find out more: https://www.timeshighered-events.com/network

Since its founding in 1920, the Harvard Graduate School of Education has been training leaders to transform education in the United States and around the globe. Today, our faculty, students, and alumni are studying and solving the most critical challenges facing education: student assessment, the achievement gap, urban education, and teacher shortages, to name just a few. Our work is shaping how people teach, learn, and lead in schools and colleges as well as in after-school programs, high-tech companies, and international organizations. The HGSE community is pushing the frontiers of education, and the effects of our entrepreneurship are improving the world.

video_title: Idabel PS After-School Program
video_description:
Today, we highlight Idabel Public Schools and their successful afterschool program that invites students to enjoy everything from cursive handwriting and archery to STEM classes and art!
"For them to have somewhere to go is very important. We don't have a lot of places for kids to go after school."
Interested in setting something like this up in YOUR district? We have grant money available! Details: https://sde.ok.gov/expanded-learning

video_title: Summer Meal Programs - Union Public Schools
video_description:
Hunger is one of the more severe roadblocks to the learning process. 
Thankfully, schools and organizations across the state have set up summer feeding sites that offer free meals to kids! 
Check out Union Public Schools - Tulsa, OK's summer feeding program, which serves 2,125 lunches and 2,125 breakfasts a day on average (WOW!), and how they've gone the extra mile to deliver meals to kids in hard-to-reach areas. Bonus: They also include fresh fruit and vegetables from local farmers - a win-win for the surrounding community. 
Find a feeding site near you: https://meals4kidsok.org/

video_description:

video_title: Project AWARE - Elk City Public Schools
video_description:
We recently visited Elk City Public Schools, one of our Project AWARE districts, to see how the initiative is helping local educators support students as they combat stress and trauma in their lives. 
"We don't have the ability to take away the hard things students are going through, but we can give them a place that's safe where they can talk about those things with someone they trust."
Project AWARE, which includes trauma-informed training and an increase of school counselors, has resulted in decreased suspension rates and an increase in attendance and academic achievement.

video_description:
MAKE YOUR OWN WHITEBOARD ANIMATIONS. CLICK THE LINK!
http://tidd.ly/69da8562 . 

This is an affiliate link. I earn commission from any sales, so Please Use!


This Playlist will cover the following common core standards: 
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.SSE.A.1
Interpret expressions that represent a quantity in terms of its context.*
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.SSE.A.1.A
Interpret parts of an expression, such as terms, factors, and coefficients.
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.SSE.A.1.B
Interpret complicated expressions by viewing one or more of their parts as a single entity. For example, interpret P(1+r)n as the product of P and a factor not depending on P.
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.SSE.A.2
Use the structure of an expression to identify ways to rewrite it. For example, see x4 - y4 as (x2)2 - (y2)2, thus recognizing it as a difference of squares that can be factored as (x2 - y2)(x2 + y2).
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.SSE.B.3
Choose and produce an equivalent form of an expression to reveal and explain properties of the quantity represented by the expression.*
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.SSE.B.3.A
Factor a quadratic expression to reveal the zeros of the function it defines.
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.SSE.B.3.B
Complete the square in a quadratic expression to reveal the maximum or minimum value of the function it defines.
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.SSE.B.3.C
Use the properties of exponents to transform expressions for exponential functions. For example the expression 1.15t can be rewritten as (1.151/12)12t ‚âà 1.01212t to reveal the approximate equivalent monthly interest rate if the annual rate is 15%.
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.SSE.B.4
Derive the formula for the sum of a finite geometric series (when the common ratio is not 1), and use the formula to solve problems. For example, calculate mortgage payments.
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.APR.A.1
Understand that polynomials form a system analogous to the integers, namely, they are closed under the operations of addition, subtraction, and multiplication; add, subtract, and multiply polynomials.
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.APR.D.7
(+) Understand that rational expressions form a system analogous to the rational numbers, closed under addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division by a nonzero rational expression; add, subtract, multiply, and divide rational expressions.
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.APR.B.3
Identify zeros of polynomials when suitable factorizations are available, and use the zeros to construct a rough graph of the function defined by the polynomial.
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.REI.A.1
Explain each step in solving a simple equation as following from the equality of numbers asserted at the previous step, starting from the assumption that the original equation has a solution. Construct a viable argument to justify a solution method.
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.REI.A.2
Solve simple rational and radical equations in one variable, and give examples showing how extraneous solutions may arise.
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.REI.C.5
Prove that, given a system of two equations in two variables, replacing one equation by the sum of that equation and a multiple of the other produces a system with the same solutions.
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.REI.C.6
Solve systems of linear equations exactly and approximately (e.g., with graphs), focusing on pairs of linear equations in two variables.
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.CED.A.1
Create equations and inequalities in one variable and use them to solve problems. Include equations arising from linear and quadratic functions, and simple rational and exponential functions.
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.CED.A.2
Create equations in two or more variables to represent relationships between quantities; graph equations on coordinate axes with labels and scales.
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.CED.A.3
Represent constraints by equations or inequalities, and by systems of equations and/or inequalities, and interpret solutions as viable or nonviable options in a modeling context. For example, represent inequalities describing nutritional and cost constraints on combinations of different foods.
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSA.CED.A.4
Rearrange formulas to highlight a quantity of interest, using the same reasoning as in solving equations. For example, rearrange Ohm's law V = IR to highlight resistance R.

Algebra 1 fundamentals of algebraic problem-solving are explained. Students will explore: foundations of Algebra, solving equations, solving inequalities, an introduction to functions, linear functions, systems of equations and inequalities, exponents and exponential functions, polynomials and factoring, quadratic functions and equations, radical expressions and equations, and data analysis and probability. Throughout the Algebra Avella's Animations, Common Core standards are taught and reinforced through video as the student learns how to apply the concepts in real-life situations.

The Behavior Intervention Plan of (applied behavior analysis) is explained through a complete overview of for educators and teachers. The video explains how the Behavior Intervention Plan known as the BIP is a part a students functional behavior assessment, also known as the FBA to classroom teachers. The components of the behavior plan are discussed. It also goes into detail how positive behavior reward systems and intervention can be included into the behavior intervention plan. Students with individualized education plans (IEP) can have a behavior plan inserted into it. These BIP plans must be evaluated for their effectiveness, and put necessary supports in place for the students. This video is part of a playlist designed for teachers, child study team, case mangers, principals, educators, behaviorists, and more to understand certain triggers for student behavior. Other videos include positive behavior supports and interventions, behavior intervention plans, rewards systems for students, classroom management, and others. video_title: Good and bad TOK, Episode 1 (pilot)
video_description:
In this pilot episode of the new series Alexey takes a TOK essay title and gives two examples in response to it. One of these examples is good, but the other one is bad. The ‚Äúbad‚Äù example may look deceptively TOK-ish, but it is actually a first-order example that would not be appropriate for a TOK essay, and would result in a massive loss of marks. Your job is to tell the difference between the two, and to figure out which of the two examples is ‚Äúgood‚Äù and which one is ‚Äúbad‚Äù. This may be harder than you think!

Alexey gives his answer at the end of the video, but formulate your own opinion before watching the answer.

video_title: Setting Goals and Following Through with Dr. Angela Duckworth
video_description: For many of us, there can be a gap between our goals and our actions. Dr. Angela Duckworth, Professor at the University of Pennsylvania School of Arts & Sciences, shares a goal setting strategy to help people follow through on their goals.

video_title: Education Reforms in Global Context: Policy & Practice
video_description:
Leaders and experts from across the globe discuss the efforts of international organizations, research institutes and governments to ensure the provision of quality education for all children. COVID-19 has added another layer of challenges vis-a-vis equity, learning and governance. How are governments responding to the COVID-19 educational disruption? What role are international organizations playing in this regard? Is EdTech an effective solution? What kind of research is being conducted to help the decision makers? Are policy makers and development practitioners using evidence to inform policy and practice? What are the key challenges facing education today, and how can different stakeholders join hands to resolve them effectively? We will be discussing all this and more with our panel of high-level experts.

Panelists:

Alice Albright - CEO of Global Partnership for Education (GPE)
Dr. Murad Raas - Minister of School Education Punjab (Pakistan)
Dr. Sharon Ravitch - Professor of Practice at the Graduate School of Education (GSE)
Jaime Saavedra - Global Director for Education, The World Bank
Matt Brossard - Chief of Education, UNICEF Office of Research
Robert Jenkins - Chief of Education, UNICEF Program Division
Edward Davis - Head Afghanistan Reconstruction Trust Fund, FCDO

Moderator: Usama Mahmud, Visiting Scholar, Penn GSE

video_title: Moving from Diversity to Equity in Higher Education
video_description: Estela Bensimon (University of Southern California) has dedicated her career to solving racial inequity and fighting for racial justice in order to build a better system of higher education for all students nationwide. Bensimon‚Äôs equity scorecard process stimulated a paradigmatic shift in higher education, inspiring faculty and administrators to accept institutional responsibility for student success. Through the Center for Urban Education, Dr. Bensimon's methods for recognizing and addressing racialized behavior have reached more than 600 higher education institutions and university systems.

video_title: RVC Ethical framework for horse sport Conference 1
video_description:
Watch the presentation of and stakeholder discussion around the ethical framework for the use of horses in sport.

Chaired by Roly Owers and featuring Dr Madeleine Campbell (RVC), Bluebell Brown (RVC), Susan Hawes and Jennifer Hall.

For a report summarising the presentations, Q&A and discussion groups please email info@worldhorsewelfare.org

video_title: Social licence and the involvement of horses in sport
video_description:
World Horse Welfare, an international charity that strives to support and improve the horse human-partnership in all its guises, hosts a panel discussion with leading equestrian figures about public perceptions of the involvement of horses in sport, and what more equestrian sports can, and need, to do to ensure continued public support.

From 11:00am to 12:00pm BST

Keynote 
‚Ä¢ Roly Owers, Chief Executive of World Horse Welfare

Panel
‚Ä¢ Lucy Higginson, Journalist (Panel Chair) 
‚Ä¢ Dr Madeleine Campbell, Senior Lecturer in human-animal interactions and ethics, RVC
‚Ä¢ Pippa Funnell MBE, Olympic eventer
‚Ä¢ Dr Barry Johnson, Chair of British Racing‚Äôs Horse Welfare Board
‚Ä¢ Christian Landolt, Dressage rider and eventer, trainer and FEI ground jury member
‚Ä¢ David Morley, Chair of the Hurlingham Polo Association Pony Welfare Committee 

Q&A with questions from audience

Summing up
‚Ä¢ Roly Owers, Chief Executive of World Horse Welfare

video_title: Webinar: Promoting positive equine wellbeing and behaviour through diet
video_description:
We welcomed equine behaviourist Rosa Verwijs back to talk to us about how good feeding practices can promote positive behaviour in our horses.

Rosa explains why forage must be the main part of every horse‚Äôs diet, and why certain behaviours may appear if a horse does not get an adequate amount. Rosa also touches on how we can best manage our horses to ensure they have as much chewing time as possible. She discussed how this can be balanced when we have horses requiring restricted nutritional intake or in situations where horses may spend more time inside than out. Rosa was joined by fellow equine behaviourist Justine Harrison to answer questions from the live audience about horse behaviour and how feeding practices can impact their wellbeing and mental health.

video_title: Webinar: Cutting Horse Costs, Not Horse Care
video_description:
We welcomed veterinarian Lucy Grieve, Blue Cross Horse Welfare Manager Ruth Court, and World Horse Welfare Field Officer Rachel Andrews to chat to us about how we can look to reduce costs whilst still maintaining high standards of care for our horses.  

We are all very aware of how expensive horses are to keep and we, as owners, often feel that the costs associated with their care spiral constantly upwards ‚Äì more so than ever with the increasing costs of feed, bedding, and services we are currently experiencing. 

Lucy, Ruth and Rachel, who are all very aware of the impacting that the Cost of Living Crisis is currently having on all horse owners and keepers, will guide us through areas where we can look to save money as well as highlighting where scrimping could impact the health and welfare of our horses.  As always, the team answers questions from the live audience at the end of the webinar.

video_title: Webinar: Myth busting: Is my horse being a pain or in pain?
video_description:
We welcomed Dr Sue Dyson back to help dispel some common myths we hear frequently about horses and some behaviours they display that we consider less desirable. 

From spooky dispositions to grumpy chestnuts, from lazy geldings to buzzy mares, Sue sheds light on what we, as owners and riders, may have missed when attempting to resolve commonly seen unwanted behaviours in our horses. 

Sue was joined by Equine Behaviourist Rosa Verwijs, who shared her knowledge and experience on what we need to consider when our horse is consistently displaying a behaviour we would rather they didn‚Äôt. Both Sue and Rosa also explain how we can become better at understanding what our horses are really trying to tell us. As always, the team answered questions from the live viewing audience at the end of the webinar.

Download the ‚Äòmyth busting‚Äô guide here - https://bit.ly/3irFUR2

video_title: ‡¥ï‡µÅ‡¥ï‡µç‡¥ï‡¥±‡¥ø‡µΩ ‡¥í‡¥∞‡µÅ ‡¥´‡µÅ‡µæ ‡¥ö‡¥ø‡¥ï‡µç‡¥ï‡µª ‡¥§‡¥Ø‡µç‡¥Ø‡¥æ‡¥±‡¥æ‡¥ï‡µç‡¥ï‡¥æ‡¥Ç ‡¥à‡¥∏‡¥ø‡¥Ø‡¥æ‡¥Ø‡¥ø | Cooker Chicken | Without Oven Grilled Chicken Roast..
video_description:
‡¥ï‡µÅ‡¥ï‡µç‡¥ï‡¥±‡¥ø‡µΩ ‡¥í‡¥∞‡µÅ ‡¥´‡µÅ‡µæ ‡¥ö‡¥ø‡¥ï‡µç‡¥ï‡µª ‡¥§‡¥Ø‡µç‡¥Ø‡¥æ‡¥±‡¥æ‡¥ï‡µç‡¥ï‡¥æ‡¥Ç ‡¥à‡¥∏‡¥ø‡¥Ø‡¥æ‡¥Ø‡¥ø / Cooker Chicken / Without Oven Grilled Chicken Roast
#cooker chicken #travel food n events #without oven chicken roast

How to make full chicken roast without oven or grill. Cooker Chicken is a  very easy, simple and time saver method using a normal pressure cooker. The marination can be  spicy Indian,arabic, continental, or others as your wish. It hardly take about 40-45 minutes cooking time.

Please check others Videos in my channel and subscribe if you like my videos.

Ingredients:
Chicken
Egg
Grama masala powder 
Chili powder 
Kashmiri chili powder 
Chili Flax's
Pepper powder
Corrainder powder
Garlic paste
Ginger paste
Kasthuri metti
Coconut Oil  
Salt as per taste

For Masala
Onion
Curry Leaf
Mint leaf
Pepper powder
Kashmiri chilli 
Grama masala powder
Coconut Oil for frying. 

Extra items:
Banana Leaf
Kalluppu ( Sea Salt)

Method of Preparation:
In a mixing bowl  combine all masala powders,coconut oil with garlic & garlic paste to make the marination paste.

Deeply stilted chicken is marinated with the above masala and let it rest in fridge for 2 to 3 hours

After 2-3 hours take this chicken from fridge,then apply all half cooked  masala and egg insert to chicken inside and stitch  open side chicken properly.

Apply sea salt as base for the cooker inside,then keep banana leaf top of the base

Then insert the chicken to the cooker (please note- no need any contact with contact with cooker body and chicken)

After this process cook chicken in pressure cooker for about 40-45 minutes or until completely cooked.
 
Here go the yummy yummy juicy fried cooker chicken.

Our comprehensive network of selected partners allows us to provide information services and advice on destination Portugal, turning your dreams into amazing experiences.

Syed Jalaluddin Surkh-Posh Bukhari was a Sufi saint and missionary and was one of our ancestors. He was a follower of Baha-ud-din Zakariya of the Suhrawardiyya order. Bukhari died on the 19th day of the 5th month 690 AH (20 May 1291 CE) in Uch, Punjab aged 95.

Saregama Music385,445,092 viewsJun 9, 2021
Badshah x Jacqueline Fernandez x Aastha Gill are back to raise the temperatures! üî•üî•

Saregama Originals Presents Badshah‚Äôs ‚ÄúPaani Paani‚Äù a duet with Aastha Gill starring Badshah and Jacqueline Fernandez. Badshah refreshes the soundscape with the romance of the strings of the Rajasthani Rawanhatta and the Kalbeliya Folk Dance. The power Duo Badshah and Aastha Gill are back with the gorgeous Jacqueline Fernandez, all set to set this summer on fire.                                                                                                                                                           

Badshah continues to celebrate and represent the cultures of India, celebrating its landscape, colours, dance and unique folk sounds and instruments that face the fear of being forgotten in this world of new age music.

video_title: The Truth About Puddles - A Short Short Film
video_description:
TAW Short Short Films 2022
This year we are happy to celebrate a 10-year anniversary of A Short, Short Film project we started back in 2012! Now, this project counts an impressive and wonderful collection of more than 70 animated short films created over the years! 

A Short, Short Film project is a collaboration between the first-year Character Animation and the first-year Computer Graphic Arts students at The Animation Workshop/VIA University College, where they work together to create 45-second short films targeted at children‚Äôs audiences. 

Eight teams consisting of five to six students work together to create their films from concept to finished 2D film in just four weeks. The starting point for their films is a few random keywords to kick off their storytelling, as well as two visual styles to inspire the visual look of the films. 

This year the project was supervised by teachers: Julia Bracegirdle, Uri Kranot, Philip Piaget, Martin Holm Agersnap-Grevy, and Liga Miezite Jensen. 
We hope you will enjoy the films!

'The Truth About Puddles' is produced by the first-year group:
Elmer L√∏demel, Tobias Madsen, Emma Dueholm, Niels Riisgaard, Rian Yu & Laura Rubio

In order to communicate visually, imagery must be used to convey information. For example, rather than writing the word caution, this is when visuals, images, symbols, signs, and other graphic designs are utilised to express information to others.
If there is no one around who can caution people or point them away from the danger, someone may choose to leverage this symbol to alert the audience or the receiver that something is dangerous. 
However, why is visual communication so crucial? It first improves retention. What people see is what they remember the most. Compared to what they observe and read. Second, visual communication is easily understood by all people. Have you ever travelled to a different nation and lacked knowledge about what to do or how to act? Visual communication aids in the simplification of complex messages so that they are understandable to all.
This is why maps and street signs are so helpful when travelling to a foreign nation, regardless of the visitor's language or age. Other examples of how visual communication is used to condense complex or extensive information includes  pie charts and bar graphs. This method of information presentation helps to create a clearer picture. 
Thirdly, it's simple to identify them. To make themselves instantly recognisable no matter where they are, businesses design eye-catching, unforgettable logos. 
Fourthly, they have a bigger impact.

Fashion Designing a dynamic and creative field that combines art, design, and business to create innovative and stylish clothing and accessories. To excel in this industry, students must undergo formal training in I I F A to acquire the necessary skills and knowledge to design and develop fashionable products that meet industry standards. I I F A presents Fashion Designing in 3 different courses like Diploma, UG and PG.
Fashion Designing diploma courses in I I F A combines a fundamental understanding of the principles and practices of fashion design. These courses focus on practical skills such as sketching, pattern making, draping, and sewing. In our I I F A Institute Students can expect to study a range of subjects, including fashion illustration, textile design, fashion merchandising, and fashion marketing. Diploma courses are shorter in duration and can be completed in one to two years.

I I F A offers Undergraduate BSc courses in Fashion Designing where students are enhanced with the skills and knowledge required to design and develop high-quality fashion products that meet fashion designing industry standards. In these courses I I F A provides expertise faculty who inculcate better understanding of fashion design processes, including research, sketching, pattern making, and garment construction. Students can expect to study a range of subjects, including fashion history, color theory, textile science, and fashion business. BSc degree in Fashion Designing is for three years.

Postgraduate courses in Fashion Designing of I I F A are designed to provide our students with advanced skills and knowledge in the field of fashion design. These courses allow students to specialize in a particular area of the field, such as fashion marketing, fashion styling, or fashion technology. Students can expect to undertake advanced projects, develop their design portfolio, and learn about emerging trends and technologies in the industry. Our students are powered with sophisticated Faculty to train them. A Master's degree in Fashion Designing typically takes two years to complete.

Fashion Designing courses provide individuals with the skills, knowledge, and creativity required to design and develop stylish and innovative fashion products. By enrolling in these courses, students can build a rewarding glamorous career in the fashion industry and bring their creative ideas to life.

CGI 3D Animated A Husky Story Short Film by Feed Me Light. Featured on http://www.cgmeetup.net/home/a-husky-story/ 

 Feed Me Light was stoked with the opportunity to produce this animation video with Night Agency, for their client Kiehl‚Äôs.

The 2-minute video with 3 trailers, was to be released on Kiehl‚Äôs YouTube channel communicating the story behind their new product Nightly Refining Micro-Peel Concentrate.

Based on the key character Jim, a small quinoa husk, the video was to tell ‚ÄòA Husky Story‚Äô, or the Unexpected Skincare Triumph of a Quinoa Husk Named Jim. In the video we travel with Jim on his journey from his home on the quinoa farm to then be a fundamental ingredient in the new Kiehl‚Äôs Micro-Peel product.

Set in a contemporary society of mice and rats, Hubert, a young and observant rat, walks by strangers in the Parisian metro as he recites poetry in his mind, full of belief in a better future. Hubert¬¥s poetry remains optimistic, despite the harsh reality of the world he lives in.

video_title: Baobab Studios‚Äô Namoo: A Conversation With Eric Darnell and Erick Oh
video_description: Join Baobab Studios‚Äô Chief Creative Officer, Eric Darnell, and Erick Oh, the Oscar-nominated director of their latest animated short film, NAMOO, as they talk about their respective journeys working for big studios such as DreamWorks Animation and Pixar, embracing new technology and working in the world of independent filmmaking. They will discuss their creative freedom from an artistic standpoint, as well as the biggest challenges they faced along the way. They will end by going into a deep dive about creating the studio‚Äôs latest animated short film, NAMOO, simultaneously for both theatrical and VR platforms. Using one of the latest state-of-the-art animation tools, Quill, along with real-time technology, NAMOO ‚Äì translated to ‚Äútree‚Äù in Korean ‚Äì is a hand-crafted narrative poem following the beautiful and heartbreaking moments of a man‚Äôs life, from beginning to end.

video_title: "Dinosauria Animated Series" | Trailer (2021)
video_description:
Created by David James Armsby.
https://www.facebook.com/davidarmsbyartist/

This is the trailer for my upcoming animated "Dinosauria" series. It's an animated anthology paleoart series of short films covering the lives of dinosaurs. There will be 5 films in the series and they range from 3-8 minutes in length.
This has been a real passion project for me. I love dinosaurs and I've treated this project as one big excuse to start drawing, sculpting, animating, and researching them! I've been hard at work on this series for many, many months now and I'm excited to finally start sharing some of it with you all! ^_^

At the moment the series only covers late Cretaceous North America/Canada but I will happily expand to different times and places if I decide to continue the series beyond 5 films.

Sound Effects From;
https://freesfx.co.uk/

Song Used:
"The Miracle of Flight" by Scott Buckley
https://www.scottbuckley.com.au/
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tKBAjqtPjGY

https://www.patreon.com/davidarmsby

video_title: "SCARY and STRANGE" | Surreal Animated Short Film (2019)
video_description:
Created by David James Armsby.
https://www.facebook.com/davidarmsbyartist/

This animated short film is a direct sequel to my previous animated short film, Merry Madness.
A terrible monster haunts a teenage girl. Every day the monster comes closer and closer but she has no intention to stop it. Even though the creature keeps her awake at night, gives her horrible nightmares and will likely tear her apart one day it has been with her for half of her life and is part of who she is.

This short film is about depression and the dangers of overly romanticising it. It's somewhat hypocritical of me to make a film with this kind of moral considering my previous work but that'll be covered more in the making-of.
I've always wanted to make a surreal horror short film. I love making surrealist/dreamlike artwork and imagery and I had a lot of fun playing around with those elements in this short film.
Hope you all enjoy this one! ^_^

Watch the original short film, "MERRY MADNESS" here!
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aPYNWTN2ogk

video_title: "MERRY MADNESS" | Dark Fairytale Animated Short Film (2019)
video_description:
Created by David James Armsby.
https://www.facebook.com/davidarmsbyartist/

"This is the story of the Rat and the Hound. A tale of Great and Terrible times!"
"Once upon a time, under a rock on a hill, there lived a Rat. Many would come to visit the Rat for he told stories and sang songs. He loved poetry and painting and merry madness without reason! He often sat and told his tales to men and women and monsters alike!"

This animation was a really fun project to work on. It's the most passionate I've been about a short film in forever. I did a colossal amount of drawings and paintings and even a pair of sculptures in preparation which will all be featured in the "Making-Of" video. I really delved deep into the design and art side of things with this short and I think this is my most visually appealing films to date. I really love this little world I've created and would love to explore it further! I think a quick sequel focussing on the Hound is inevitable.
Really hope you guys like this short film as much as I enjoyed working on it. ^_^

video_title: Oscar's Oasis - Ep 12 -  Walking On The Moon
The Twisted Whiskers Show   Season 2  Ep 3
video_description:
The Full HD Episode of popular cartoon shows The Twisted Whiskers. It is an animated series where silly cats and dogs interact in typical pet situations that become "twisted" as all the characters get into funny and unexpected misadventures. Each character has a unique personality and they are caught between a variety of themes, places and situations.

It has hilarious characters that can wrap even the most mundane of circumstances into something absurd. The off-kilter look and attitude of the characters gives them strong cross-Generational and cross-cultural appeal with everyone - kids, tweens, teens and adults.

This episode titled HIGH WIRE HIGH JINKS, features Gooser, the dog and his master who are relaxing on a bright sunny afternoon. All of a sudden, a squirrel shows up and keeps troubling and teasing Gooser. The dog gets angry on the squirrel and starts barking. His master unknowing Gooser's reason behind his irritation warns and ties him up. Watch this episode to find out if Gooser was able to teach a lesson to the squirrel‚Ä¶

This animated TV shows has been written & directed by Bill Kopp. Music by John W.F. Goode, Title theme song by Ryan Wiesbrock.
